  "signature": "ed25519:b2d4f6a8c0e2b4d6f8a0c2e4b6d8f0a2c4e6b8d0f2a4c6e8b0d2f4a6c8e0b2d4",
  "hasCredibilityFactor": [
    {
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "factorType": "Software quality assurance",
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "requiredLevel": 3,
      "achievedLevel": 3,
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "acceptanceCriteria": "SQA plan covers version control, issue tracking, and regression testing for all simulation codes (Ansys Mechanical 2022R2, custom pre/post scripts). Achieved when all scripts are under Git version control with tagged releases, and a regression test suite passes with zero critical failures.",
      "rationale": "All three modeling teams (FDA, Ansys, DePuy Synthes) operate under documented SQA plans. Ansys Mechanical 2022R2 is a commercially validated solver with NIST-traceable benchmark results. Custom pre- and post-processing scripts are maintained in a Git repository with tagged releases corresponding to each simulation campaign. A regression test suite of 47 benchmark cases was executed prior to the validation study; all cases passed within specified tolerances. Issue tracking is performed via JIRA with mandatory peer review for any code change affecting QoI computation."
    },
    {
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "factorType": "Numerical code verification",
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "requiredLevel": 3,
      "achievedLevel": 3,
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "acceptanceCriteria": "Code verification achieved when the FEA solver reproduces ASME V&V 10 benchmark solutions for linear elastic beam bending and contact problems within 1% of analytical reference values.",
      "rationale": "Ansys Mechanical 2022R2 has been verified against ASME V&V 10 benchmark problems, including linear elastic beam bending (Timoshenko beam, error < 0.3%) and Hertzian contact (error < 0.8%). The pedicle screw geometry was additionally verified using a simplified cantilever beam approximation; FEA stiffness agreed with the analytical solution within 0.6%. These results confirm that the numerical implementation is free of coding errors for the physics relevant to this COU."
    },
    {
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "factorType": "Discretization error",
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "requiredLevel": 3,
      "achievedLevel": 3,
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "acceptanceCriteria": "Discretization error is acceptable when a formal mesh convergence study demonstrates that QoI values change by less than 2% between the selected mesh and the next refinement level, and the Richardson extrapolation-based GCI is below 3%.",
      "rationale": "A three-level mesh convergence study was performed on the non-cannulated 7.5 mm screw geometry. Mesh densities of 0.4 mm, 0.25 mm, and 0.15 mm element size at the screw-rod interface were evaluated. Construct stiffness changed by 1.1% between the 0.25 mm and 0.15 mm meshes; the GCI was 1.8%. The 0.25 mm mesh was selected for the production runs as the optimal balance of accuracy and computational cost. Yield force and force at 40 mm displacement showed similar convergence behavior (GCI < 2.4% for both)."
    },
    {
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "factorType": "Numerical solver error",
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "requiredLevel": 2,
      "achievedLevel": 2,
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "acceptanceCriteria": "Solver error is acceptable when iterative convergence criteria are set to force residual < 1e-4 and displacement residual < 1e-5, and all production runs converge within these criteria without user intervention.",
      "rationale": "All production simulations used the Ansys Mechanical sparse direct solver with iterative refinement. Convergence criteria were set to force residual < 1e-4 and displacement residual < 1e-5. All 11 simulation runs (matching the experimental specimens) converged within these criteria. No divergence or non-convergence events were recorded. Solver log files are archived in the project repository."
    },
    {
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "factorType": "Use error",
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "requiredLevel": 3,
      "achievedLevel": 3,
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "acceptanceCriteria": "Use error is mitigated when a documented simulation workflow with mandatory peer review is followed, and an independent analyst reproduces at least two QoI values within 1% of the primary analyst's results.",
      "rationale": "A detailed simulation workflow document (SOP-FEA-001, Rev C) was followed by all three modeling teams. Boundary conditions, material assignments, and contact definitions were independently reviewed by a second analyst on each team prior to result extraction. An inter-analyst reproducibility check was performed: an independent FDA analyst reproduced construct stiffness and yield force for specimen #3 within 0.4% and 0.7% respectively. No use errors were identified during the review process."
    },
    {
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "factorType": "Model form",
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "requiredLevel": 3,
      "achievedLevel": 3,
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "acceptanceCriteria": "Model form is adequate when the constitutive model (bilinear isotropic hardening for Ti-6Al-4V) is validated against coupon-level tensile test data, and the contact formulation reproduces screw-rod interface behavior observed in sub-model benchmarks.",
      "rationale": "The constitutive model (bilinear isotropic hardening, E = 114 GPa, sigma_y = 880 MPa, tangent modulus = 2.1 GPa) was calibrated and validated against ASTM E8 tensile test data for Ti-6Al-4V bar stock from the same material lot as the test constructs. The frictional contact formulation (augmented Lagrangian, mu = 0.2) was validated against a sub-model benchmark replicating the screw-rod interface under pure bending; predicted contact pressure distribution agreed with photoelastic measurements within 8%. Large-deformation effects (NLGEOM on) were included to capture geometric nonlinearity at displacements approaching 40 mm."
    },
    {
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "factorType": "Model inputs",
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "requiredLevel": 3,
      "achievedLevel": 3,
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "acceptanceCriteria": "Model inputs are adequately characterized when material properties are sourced from lot-specific coupon tests, geometric dimensions are measured from each physical specimen via CMM with uncertainty < 0.05 mm, and input uncertainty is propagated to QoI uncertainty via Monte Carlo sampling (N >= 500).",
      "rationale": "Material properties were measured from three tensile coupons machined from the same Ti-6Al-4V bar stock used to manufacture the test constructs. Geometric dimensions (screw outer diameter, rod diameter, pedicle block bore diameter) were measured for each of the 11 specimens using a coordinate measuring machine (CMM) with expanded uncertainty of 0.03 mm (k=2). Specimen-specific geometric dimensions were incorporated into each of the 11 simulation models. Input uncertainty propagation was performed via Monte Carlo sampling (N=1000) over material property distributions; the resulting QoI uncertainty was incorporated into the validation metric E/uval."
    },
    {
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "factorType": "Test samples",
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "requiredLevel": 3,
      "achievedLevel": 3,
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "acceptanceCriteria": "Test sample adequacy is established when N >= 10 specimens are tested across at least two independent laboratories, and specimen traceability to manufacturing lot is documented.",
      "rationale": "Eleven non-cannulated 7.5 mm pedicle screw constructs were tested: six at Laboratory 1 (FDA CDRH) and five at Laboratory 2 (DePuy Synthes). All specimens were manufactured from the same production lot (Lot #DPS-2021-NC75-004) and are traceable via serial number. The sample size of N=11 provides adequate statistical power for the validation metric calculation and is consistent with ASTM F1717 requirements. Inter-laboratory variability in construct stiffness was 4.2% (CV), within expected manufacturing and assembly tolerances."
    },
    {
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "factorType": "Test conditions",
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "requiredLevel": 3,
      "achievedLevel": 2,
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "acceptanceCriteria": "Test conditions are adequate when at least two independent loading configurations (e.g., compression-bending at two different offset distances or load rates) are evaluated to demonstrate that the model correctly captures load-path sensitivity.",
      "rationale": "All experimental tests were conducted under a single ASTM F1717 compression-bending configuration (10 mm anterior offset, quasi-static loading at 5 mm/min). While this configuration is the regulatory standard for pedicle screw constructs and is directly relevant to the COU, the validation evidence is limited to a single test condition. The model has not been challenged across varying offset distances or load rates within this validation campaign. This limitation is acknowledged; the achieved level of 2 reflects that the test conditions are well-controlled and fully documented but do not span the parameter space that would be required for a Gradation 3 rating. The single-condition constraint is accepted given that ASTM F1717 defines a standardized protocol and regulatory precedent supports its use as the sole validation benchmark for this device class."
    },
    {
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "factorType": "Equivalency of input parameters",
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "requiredLevel": 3,
      "achievedLevel": 3,
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "acceptanceCriteria": "Equivalency is established when all model input parameters (geometry, material, boundary conditions, loading) are traceable to experimentally measured values for each specimen, and any unmeasured parameters are justified by literature or sensitivity analysis.",
      "rationale": "All primary model inputs (screw and rod geometry, material properties, pedicle block dimensions, load application point) were matched to experimentally measured values on a per-specimen basis. The coefficient of friction at the screw-rod interface (mu = 0.2) was not directly measured; a sensitivity analysis showed that varying mu from 0.15 to 0.30 changed predicted construct stiffness by less than 3%, which is within the experimental variability. Boundary conditions (fixed base, axial-compressive load at 10 mm anterior offset) were verified against test machine setup photographs and load cell calibration records."
    },
    {
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "factorType": "Output comparison",
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "requiredLevel": 3,
      "achievedLevel": 3,
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "acceptanceCriteria": "Output comparison is adequate when the validation metric E/uval is computed for all three QoIs using ASME V&V 10.1 methodology and all values are below 1.96 (95% confidence interval criterion), AND the percentage difference between mean predicted and mean experimental QoI is below 10%.",
      "rationale": "Validation metrics were computed per ASME V&V 10.1 for all three QoIs. E/uval values: construct stiffness 1.12, yield force 0.87, force at 40 mm displacement 1.44 \u2014 all below the 1.96 threshold. Percentage differences between mean FEA and mean experimental values: stiffness 3.8%, yield force 5.1%, force at 40 mm 7.3% \u2014 all below the 10% acceptance bound. The validation metric calculation incorporated both experimental measurement uncertainty (from inter-specimen variability and instrument calibration) and simulation input uncertainty (from Monte Carlo propagation). Results are reported separately for each of the 11 specimen-specific simulations and for the ensemble mean."
    },
    {
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "factorType": "Relevance of the quantities of interest",
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "requiredLevel": 3,
      "achievedLevel": 3,
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "acceptanceCriteria": "QoI relevance is established when each QoI is directly linked to a regulatory submission requirement or a clinically meaningful failure mode, and the QoI is extractable from both the simulation and the physical test without ambiguity.",
      "rationale": "The three QoIs (construct stiffness, yield force, force at 40 mm displacement) are the primary metrics specified in ASTM F1717 and are required outputs in FDA 510(k) submissions for pedicle screw systems. Construct stiffness is directly related to load-sharing behavior in the spine; yield force defines the onset of permanent deformation; force at 40 mm displacement characterizes post-yield energy absorption relevant to fatigue and fracture risk. All three QoIs are unambiguously extractable from both the load-displacement curve (experimental) and the FEA force-displacement output. The mapping between simulation output and experimental measurement was verified by overlaying representative force-displacement curves."
    },
    {
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "factorType": "Relevance of the validation activities to the COU",
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "requiredLevel": 3,
      "achievedLevel": 3,
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "acceptanceCriteria": "Validation activity relevance is established when the validation scenario (geometry, material, loading, boundary conditions) matches the COU scenario in all primary parameters, and any differences are bounded by sensitivity analysis.",
      "rationale": "The validation activity is a direct simulation of the ASTM F1717 test performed on the same non-cannulated 7.5 mm screw design that is the subject of the COU. The validation geometry, material, loading protocol, and boundary conditions are identical to the COU scenario. The only difference between the validation activity and the intended COU use is that the COU may eventually be applied to predict performance under in vivo loading conditions; however, the current submission scope is limited to the F1717 bench test prediction, making the validation directly applicable. The high degree of overlap between validation scenario and COU scenario supports a Gradation 3 rating for this factor."
    }
  ],
  "hasWeakener": [],
  "hasDecisionRecord": {
    "id": "https://uofa.net/synth/decision/nagaraja-cou1-decision-20260419",
    "type": "DecisionRecord",
    "actor": "https://uofa.net/synth/actor/nagaraja-credibility-assessment-team",
    "role": "Credibility assessment team",
    "outcome": "Accepted",
    "rationale": "The overall credibility assessment for COU1 is Accepted at Medium assurance level. Twelve of thirteen V&V 40 credibility factors achieved their required level (Gradation 3). One factor (Test conditions) achieved Gradation 2 against a required level of 3, reflecting the single-condition ASTM F1717 test protocol; this shortfall is accepted given regulatory precedent and the direct correspondence between the validation scenario and the COU. All three QoIs passed the pre-specified validation metric thresholds (E/uval < 1.96, percentage difference < 10%). The model ensemble approach (three independent modeling teams) provides additional confidence in the robustness of the FEA predictions. The credibility assessment team concludes that the simulation evidence is sufficient to support the intended regulatory decision.",
    "decidedAt": "2026-04-19T00:00:00Z"
  },
